<h1>Language Documentation &amp; Maintenance</h1>

<h2>Ticha Project</h2>

<p>Since 2013, I have been a research assistant on the <a href="http://ticha.haverford.edu" target="_blank">Ticha Project</a>, a digital text explorer of Colonial Zapotec documents (<a href="publications.html#cite-ticha">Lillehaugen et al. 2016</a>).  Among other projects, I have worked on the digitization of <a href="https://ticha.haverford.edu/en/texts/handwritten/" target=_blank">Zapotec manuscripts</a> and the transcription and XML-encoding of <a href="https://ticha.haverford.edu/en/arte/" target="_blank">Cordova's <i>Arte</i></a>.</p>


<h2>Valley Zapotec Talking Dictionaries</h2>

<p>In 2015-2016, as part of the Linguistics Field School (NSF REU Site Grant #1461056) in Oaxaca, I helped build <a href="http://talkingdictionary.swarthmore.edu/zapotecs/" target="_blank">Talking Dictionaries</a> for three Valley Zapotec languages (Lillehaugen et al. <a href="publications.html#cite-tlacochahuaya-td">2016a</a>, <a href="publications.html#cite-sanlucas-td">2016b</a>,<a href="publications.html#cite-teotitlan-td">2016c</a>).</p> 

<h2>Indigenous Languge Engagement on Twitter</h2>

<p>I actively engage with indigenous languages on Twitter (<a href="https://twitter.com/mayhplumb" target="_blank">&#64;mayhplumb</a>).  In 2016 and 2017 I participated in the Voces del Valle Project to encourage indigenous language speakers to write on Twitter (see <a href="https://twitter.com/search?f=tweets&vertical=default&q=%23UsaTuVoz&src=tyah" target="_blank">#UsaTuVoz</a>).</p>



